The issue with the current implementation is that it is solely relying on specific keywords to identify the presence of tables or columns. This approach is not robust enough as it may not capture all variations of tables and columns.

To address this, we need to update the function to look for patterns that are commonly associated with tables or columns. This can involve checking for consistent spacing, alignments, and repeated patterns within the input text.

Here is the updated function to address these issues:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(inputText) {
  // Check for patterns indicating the presence of tables or columns
  const lines = inputText.split('\n').filter(line => line.trim() !== '');
  const firstLineLength = lines[0].trim().length;
  const isColumnBased = lines.every(line => line.trim().length === firstLineLength);

  if (isColumnBased) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // Check for table patterns based on consistent spacing and alignments
  const lineLengths = lines.map(line => line.trim().length);
  const isTableBased = lineLengths.every((length, index) => index === 0 || length === lineLengths[0]);

  if (isTableBased) {
    return "TABLE";
  }

  return "NORMAL";
}
```

In the updated function, we split the input text into lines and analyze the lengths and alignments of the lines to determine if they match the patterns commonly observed in tables or columns. This approach improves the accuracy of identifying tables or columns within the input text.
